00:50:28.700 --> 00:50:36.140
three juggling made it 50% faster for request response. And URL lib is no longer URL lib-ish.

00:50:37.260 --> 00:50:40.440
Yeah, so that was the other part, going back to Virxwig.

00:50:42.720 --> 00:50:47.080
So we removed the string bytes testing all over the place.

00:50:48.800 --> 00:50:57.000
And Virxwig, this was, again, historically because of, like, Python 2 versus Python 3 differences and then compatibility and stuff.

00:50:57.160 --> 00:51:00.920
But another of the changes in Python 3 was URL lib.

00:51:02.740 --> 00:51:05.120
In Python 2, there was, like, URL lib and URL lib 2.

00:51:06.040 --> 00:51:08.540
And that's why there's also the project URL of three now.

00:51:08.780 --> 00:51:08.920
Yeah.

00:51:11.320 --> 00:51:16.180
But Python 3 kind of consolidated that back into URL lib with sub packages instead.

00:51:17.800 --> 00:51:20.360
So it kind of changed the interfaces and where everything was.

00:51:20.840 --> 00:51:28.740
So at the time, it made sense for VerixFug to just copy that code into our own code base

00:51:28.880 --> 00:51:34.700
and then make our own tweaks to it to be compatible with everything.

00:51:36.720 --> 00:51:43.520
But what that ended up meaning was we had an entire copy of URLib with our own tweaks in our code base.

00:51:44.720 --> 00:51:47.260
And then we weren't keeping up with changes.

00:51:47.580 --> 00:51:52.820
So like CPython has like 100 different core devs on it.

00:51:52.820 --> 00:52:01.200
I mean, they're not all paying attention to URLib, but they're making regular security updates or just performance improvements and that sort of stuff.

00:52:02.440 --> 00:52:04.780
And we're not getting any of those benefits because we now have like this

00:52:04.940 --> 00:52:06.560
vendor copy that we've changed ourselves.

00:52:06.700 --> 00:52:08.340
We couldn't even bring in the changes.

00:52:09.100 --> 00:52:10.560
And just like the string bytes everywhere,

00:52:12.080 --> 00:52:16.220
having that our own copy of that really complex low level code made it harder

00:52:16.300 --> 00:52:19.920
to reason about the code and be like maintain it.

00:52:21.720 --> 00:52:23.100
And all this stuff is kind of like,

00:52:24.080 --> 00:52:25.940
it's not the essential parts of Werkzeug.

00:52:26.040 --> 00:52:28.660
Werkzeug is like trying to be the WSGI utilities and stuff.

00:52:28.760 --> 00:52:31.980
It's not trying to be like every single possible.

00:52:32.110 --> 00:52:32.800
Like it's not trying to,

00:52:32.880 --> 00:52:35.500
we don't need to make our own URL of utility and everything

00:52:35.680 --> 00:52:36.280
to be virtually.

00:52:37.320 --> 00:52:37.720
Yeah.

00:52:37.840 --> 00:52:39.960
So that was another big one where I identified like,

00:52:40.110 --> 00:52:42.600
okay, this is just a lot of complexity.

00:52:42.610 --> 00:52:46.460
I didn't actually expect this to be a performance improvement,

00:52:47.260 --> 00:52:50.480
but when I actually went through and removed URL lib

00:52:50.740 --> 00:52:53.820
and our own copy and replaced it with Python's version,

00:52:54.680 --> 00:52:58.500
we got like a 30% speed up just on our own.

00:52:58.660 --> 00:53:03.580
So the combined of those two big changes was like about a 50% speed up in our request response.

00:53:03.580 --> 00:53:04.060
Yeah, that's awesome.

